04776nam a22005775i 9780822386933DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223869337 a10.1515/97808223869332doi  a(DE-B1597)553258  a(OCoLC)1077375389  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aMUS0290002bisacsh1 aWeheliye, Alexander G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhonographies :bGrooves in Sonic Afro-Modernity /cAlexander G. Weheliye. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntro: It’s Beginning to Feel Like . . . -- t1 Hearing Sonic Afro-Modernity -- t2 ‘‘I Am I Be’’: A Subject of Sonic Afro-Modernity -- t3 In the Mix -- t4 Consuming Sonic Technologies -- t5 Sounding Diasporic Citizenship -- tOutro: Thinking Sound/Sound Thinking (Slipping into the Breaks Remix) -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPhonographies explores the numerous links and relays between twentieth-century black cultural production and sound technologies from the phonograph to the Walkman. Highlighting how black authors, filmmakers, and musicians have actively engaged with recorded sound in their work, Alexander G. Weheliye contends that the interplay between sound technologies and black music and speech enabled the emergence of modern black culture, of what he terms “sonic Afro-modernity.” He shows that by separating music and speech from their human sources, sound-recording technologies beginning with the phonograph generated new modes of thinking, being, and becoming. Black artists used these new possibilities to revamp key notions of modernity—among these, ideas of subjectivity, temporality, and community. Phonographies is a powerful argument that sound technologies are integral to black culture, which is, in turn, fundamental to Western modernity.Weheliye surveys literature, film, and music to focus on engagements with recorded sound. He offers substantial new readings of canonical texts by W. E. B. Du Bois and Ralph Ellison, establishing dialogues between these writers and popular music and film ranging from Louis Armstrong’s voice to DJ mixing techniques to Darnell Martin’s 1994 movie I Like It Like That. Looking at how questions of diasporic belonging are articulated in contemporary black musical practices, Weheliye analyzes three contemporary Afro-diasporic musical acts: the Haitian and African American rap group the Fugees, the Afro- and Italian-German rap collective Advanced Chemistry, and black British artist Tricky and his partner Martina. Phonographies imagines the African diaspora as a virtual sounding space, one that is marked, in the twentieth century and twenty-first, by the circulation of culture via technological reproductions—records and tapes, dubbing and mixing, and more.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansvMusicy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAfrican AmericansxMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aBlacksvMusicy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aBlacksxMusicy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusic and literaturexHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular musicxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aSoundxRecording and reproducingxSocial aspects. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Pop Vocal.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822386933zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822386933423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cove